<worksheet xml:id="activities-cardinality">

<activity><p>
	Use the definition of <term><xref ref="definition-cardinality-itself" text="custom">cardinality</xref></term>
	to verify that <m> \card{A} = 8 </m> for <md> A = \{1,2,4,8,16,32,64,128\} </md>.
</p></activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-cardinality-subset-of-finite">
	<introduction>
		<p> The steps below will guide you through a proof of the following statement. </p>
		<blockquote><p> If <m> B </m> is finite and <m> A \subseteq B </m>, then <m> A </m> is also finite. </p></blockquote>
	</introduction>
	<task xml:id="activity-cardinality-subset-of-finite-unravel-finite"><p>
		Start by assuming that <m> B </m> is finite.
		Write out what this means.
		(You may do this using the technical definition of
		<term><xref ref="definition-cardinality-finite-set" text="title" /></term>,
		or you may do this using the sequence characterization of finiteness in <xref ref="fact-cardinality-finite-set-finite-sequence" />.)
	</p></task>
	<task xml:id="activity-cardinality-subset-of-finite-unravel-subset"><p>
		Now add the assumption that <m> A \subseteq B </m>.
		Try to use your technical expression of the assumption <q><m> B </m> is finite</q> from
		<xref ref="activity-cardinality-subset-of-finite-unravel-finite" text="type-local" />
		to determine a similar technical expression of the desired conclusion <q><m> A </m> is finite.</q>
	</p></task>
</activity>

<activity>
	<statement>
		<p> Use the sequence characterization of finiteness in <xref ref="fact-cardinality-finite-set-finite-sequence" /> to prove the following statement. </p>
		<blockquote><p> If <m> A </m> and <m> B </m> are finite and do not intersect, then <m> \abs{A \sqcup B} = \abs{A} + \abs{B} </m>. </p></blockquote>
	</statement>
	<hint><p>
		Use separate finite sequences to <q>count</q> the elements of <m> A </m> and <m> B </m>.
		Then use these two sequences to build a sequence that <q>counts</q> the elements of <m> A \sqcup B </m>.
	</p></hint>
</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-cardinality-same-size">
	<!-- \label{EXER::same.size} -->
	<introduction><p>
		In each of the following, demonstrate that the two sets satisfy the technical definition of
		<term><xref ref="definition-cardinality-same-size" text="title" /></term>
		by explicitly describing a bijection between them.
	</p></introduction>
	<task><p> The set of natural numbers and the set of positive natural numbers. </p></task>
	<task><p> The set of natural numbers and the set of natural numbers that are greater than <m> 9,999,999 </m>. </p></task>
	<task><p> The set of even natural numbers and the set of odd natural numbers. </p></task>
	<task><p> The set of even natural numbers and the set of natural numbers. </p></task>
	<task><p> The set of natural numbers and the set of integer powers of <m> 2 </m>. </p></task>
	<!-- OLD replaced by more detailed version in next activity
	<li> \label{EXER::same.size::power.set.v.words} The power set of <m> \{a,b,c,d,e\} </m> and the set of all words in the alphabet <m> \Sigma = \{T,F\} </m> of length <m> 5 </m>.
	-->
</activity>

<activity xml:id="activity-cardinality-power-set-vs-strings">
	<introduction><p> Set <md><mrow> A \amp = \{\mathrm{a},\mathrm{b},\mathrm{c},\mathrm{d},\mathrm{e}\}, \amp \Sigma \amp = \{\mathrm{Y},\mathrm{N}\} </mrow></md>. </p></introduction>
	<task xml:id="activity-cardinality-power-set-vs-strings-bij">
		<statement><p>
			Demonstrate that <m> \powset{A} </m> and <m> \words{\Sigma}_5 </m> have the same size.
			(Recall that <m> \words{\Sigma}_5 </m> means the set of words in <m> \words{\Sigma} </m> of length exactly <m> 5 </m>.)
			Do this not by determining the cardinality of each of the two sets,
			but by showing that the sets satisfy the technical definition of
			<term><xref ref="definition-cardinality-same-size" text="title" /></term>.
			As in <xref ref="activity-cardinality-same-size" />, this will require that you
			explicitly describe a bijection between the two sets.
		</p></statement>
		<hint><p>
			Think of a <m> 5 </m>-letter word in the alphabet <m> \Sigma </m> as the answers to five yes-or-no questions.
			How does such a string of answers correspond to some subset of <m> A </m>?
		</p></hint>
	</task>
	<task>
		<p>
		Describe how you could use the bijection you set up in
		<xref ref="activity-cardinality-power-set-vs-strings-bij" text="type-local" />
		to turn the problem of counting the number of subsets of <m> A </m> that have exactly <m> 3 </m> elements into a problem of counting a related collection of words in the alphabet <m> \Sigma </m>.
		</p><p>
		(<em>Note:</em>
		You are not asked to actually determine the number of such subsets.
		You are only asked to describe <em>how</em> the result of <xref ref="activity-cardinality-power-set-vs-strings-bij" text="type-local" />
		can be adapted to this counting problem.)
		</p>
	</task>
</activity>

</worksheet>
